<p class=3D"x_bodyText" data-olk-copy-source=3D"MessageBody">Seventy-four s=
tatus representatives and local executive council (LEC) officers from 26 of=
 ALPA's pilot groups were at the Association's headquarters in McLean, Va.,=
 earlier this week to take part in the union's premier educational event: t=
he Leadership Training Conference. Each year, incoming elected local counci=
l leaders from both Canada and the United States participate in this unique=
 training opportunity to learn more about their duties and the many resourc=
es the union provides to help them make the most of their terms of office.<=
/p>
<div class=3D"x_bodyText" aria-hidden=3D"true">&nbsp;</div>
<p class=3D"x_bodyText">=E2=80=9CThe future of our union is in this room,=
=E2=80=9D said ALPA president Capt. Jason Ambrosi, who welcomed attendees a=
nd discussed his experiences as a former LEC officer. =E2=80=9CALPA is a bo=
ttom-up organization. As local representatives, you have the ability to cre=
ate policy and set the direction of our union for years to come.=E2=80=9D</=
p>
<div class=3D"x_bodyText" aria-hidden=3D"true">&nbsp;</div>
<p class=3D"x_bodyText">This year's conference featured a new format, desig=
ned to highlight the tiered responsibilities of each local council=E2=80=99=
s status reps. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s important for you to understand the di=
fferent hats you wear,=E2=80=9D remarked F/O Tyler Hawkins (UAL), the ALPA =
Professional Development Group=E2=80=99s Leadership Committee chair. In add=
ition to their local council and LEC obligations, status reps also serve as=
 members of their pilot groups=E2=80=99 master executive councils and the u=
nion=E2=80=99s Board of Directors, ALPA=E2=80=99s highest governing body.</=
p>
<div class=3D"x_bodyText" aria-hidden=3D"true">&nbsp;</div>
<p class=3D"x_bodyText">Accordingly, Tuesday=E2=80=99s interactive presenta=
tions and breakout sessions highlighted the day-to-day considerations for r=
unning a local council, Wednesday=E2=80=99s coursework concentrated on the =
demands of overseeing a pilot group, and Thursday=E2=80=99s segments focuse=
d on Association-wide concerns and priorities. Conference attendees partici=
pated in an =E2=80=9Copen house=E2=80=9D event, allowing them to meet and g=
et to know ALPA=E2=80=99s professional staff and committees. They also had =
plenty of opportunities to network with their industry peers from other pil=
ot groups during breaks and scheduled social events.</p>
<div class=3D"x_bodyText" aria-hidden=3D"true">&nbsp;</div>
<p class=3D"x_bodyText">Hawkins and the ALPA Leadership Committee members s=
erved as moderators for the three-day event. Look for more details about th=
is year=E2=80=99s Leadership Training Conference in the March 2026 issue of=
&nbsp;<em>Air Line Pilot</em>&nbsp;magazine.</p>

